    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down.</hi> | Beckenham | <hi rend="print">Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Aug. 3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Bence Jones</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I must thank you cordially for your very kind invitation;<ref target="#foot.f2"/> but my stomach, not withstanding all your good aid, is too diabolical to allow me to visit anywhere except at a very few of my nearest relations, where I can behave as I like. We shall, also, start soon for a visit to my son.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> If it had been possible I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> thoroughily have enjoyed accepting your kindness.— Your letter has been an <hi rend="underline">immense</hi> relief to me; but I will be careful &amp; try &amp; not work too hard.</p>
<p>Yours very gratefully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 Beckenham] <hi rend="italic">before del</hi> ‘<hi rend="italic">Bromley.</hi>’ </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.3 , also,] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7293.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">letter from H. B. Jones, 2 August 1870</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7293.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">letter from H. B. Jones, 2 August 1870</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD, with <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1230.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Leonard Darwin</ref>, visited <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Erasmus Darwin</ref> in Southampton from 13 to 26 August 1870 (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242), CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
        </div>        
            
